<p><strong>Example: Andy Murray</strong></p>

<p>Andy Murray found focus only after a 2008 Olympic defeat:Â </p>

<blockquote>
  <p>â€œI was so excited to play in the Olympics and be part of it that I was doing a lot of media. I learnt a lot from that match. It was one of the toughest losses of my career, and I donâ€™t plan to repeat the experience on Wednesday. I was going to the opening ceremony, I was trying to speak to all of the athletes and take pictures with them, I was collecting the pins from each team - I was loving being part of it. â€œBut when I lost, I thought, â€˜Why was I doing all that stuff? Iâ€™m here to win matches, Iâ€™m not here to collect pins.â€™ I loved going to the opening ceremony but had to think, â€˜Is that the best thing for my preparation?â€™Â </p>
</blockquote>

<p>He got very close to winning <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WzCB4YQXPeM">2012 Wimbledon Final</a>, but you can see by how much it hurt him that he really wanted it.</p>

<p>But he then won the <a href="https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/tennis/9454659/Andy-Murray-I-would-not-trade-my-London-2012-Olympic-gold-for-a-first-Wimbledon-title.html">Olympic 2012 Gold</a>, and that broke the barrier. He found the elusive winning mentality in the middle of the career, unlike Jana Novotna or Goran Ivanisevic - who, despite having the opportunities to win, Â struggled for years because they lacked the magical sense ofÂ â€œknowing winningâ€, and the focus and inner belief that comes with it.
Prior to winning the Olympic Gold, Murray was stuck in the same mire ofÂ uncertainty and doubt that did not leave Ivanisevic and Novotna through much of their career. But winning the Olympic gold set him free of it - it unlocked the winning mentality, and their was no going back. Winning gives you a mental grasp of your target, and once you know it,Â Â darkness and uncertainty disappears.Â </p>

<p>Contrast Murray with <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eugenie_Bouchard">Eugenie Bouchard</a>, who after losing the 2014 Wimbledon Final, started believing that she is destined for winning even before actually doing it, and totally lost it.</p>

